{"key":"post-10358863","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10358863</id>\n<content>That looks like about the right number of holes.&amp;nbsp; Calibrate your hygrometer.&amp;nbsp; You also want to make sure your perlite is fluffed up by raking it with your fingers to create furrows.&amp;nbsp; This will increase the surface area.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;There's no way it's dropping to 60%, so I suspect your hygrometer isn't calibrated or you're hanging it on the side where the sensor is exposed to the holes.&amp;nbsp; Put the hygrometer in the middle of the tub after calibration and I'll bet your humidity is fine.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10358881</next>\n<prev>10358855</prev>\n<first>10358831</first>\n<last>10358969</last>\n<when>1242677977</when>\n<utime>05/18/09 11:19 PM</utime>\n</post>"}